<h2>Expert Tips</h2>

<ol>
<li>Buy non-vintage Brut first, then move into vintage or grower bottles once you know the style you prefer.</li>
<li>Use a wine shop with cold storage if you are spending over $100, because storage quality matters as much as producer quality.</li>
<li>Choose Blanc de Blancs when you want a sharper, leaner profile and Pinot Noir-heavy blends when you want more body.</li>
<li>For gifting, buy the best known producer within budget rather than chasing a niche bottle the recipient may not recognize.</li>
<li>Do not overchill prestige Champagne. Around 45-50°F keeps the mousse fresh without muting the aroma.</li>
<li>If the meal is the focus, spend less on label prestige and more on matching the bottle style to the menu.</li>
<li>When comparing two similarly priced bottles, favor the merchant with better storage and faster inventory turnover.</li>
<li>Read the back label for importer and producer details. Clear sourcing usually beats anonymous luxury packaging.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>How long does Champagne last after opening?</h3>
<p>Champagne maintains quality for 3-5 days when properly stored with a Champagne stopper in the refrigerator. The carbonation gradually diminishes, but the wine remains drinkable. Vintage Champagnes often hold better than non-vintage due to higher acidity levels.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Is vintage Champagne always better than non-vintage?</h3>
<p>Not necessarily. Non-vintage Champagnes represent house style through consistent blending across multiple years. Vintage bottles showcase exceptional harvest years but vary significantly in quality. Many non-vintage releases from top houses surpass mediocre vintage offerings.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between Brut and Extra Brut Champagne?</h3>
<p>Brut Champagne contains 0-12 grams of residual sugar per liter, while Extra Brut allows only 0-6 grams. Extra Brut styles taste noticeably drier and more austere, highlighting mineral and citrus notes over rounder, softer flavors found in regular Brut.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should I decant Champagne before serving?</h3>
<p>Never decant Champagne. Decanting eliminates the carbonation that defines the wine style. Serve directly from chilled bottles into proper flutes to preserve bubbles and aromatics. The only exception is very old Champagnes with sediment, which require careful pouring rather than decanting.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I identify authentic Champagne versus sparkling wine?</h3>
<p>Check the label for "Champagne" designation and French origin. Authentic bottles display the producer name, village location, and often include "Appellation Champagne Contrôlée." Avoid bottles labeled "Champagne-style" or similar terms, as these indicate sparkling wines from other regions.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What causes different bubble sizes in Champagne?</h3>
<p>Fine, persistent bubbles result from proper secondary fermentation and adequate aging on lees. Larger, aggressive bubbles often indicate forced carbonation or insufficient aging. Temperature also affects bubble size—properly chilled Champagne displays smaller, more elegant bubbles.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Are magnum bottles worth the extra cost?</h3>
<p>Magnums (1.5L) often provide better aging conditions due to slower maturation and less oxygen exposure per volume of wine. For special occasions or cellaring, the premium over two regular bottles may justify the superior development. However, half-bottles age too quickly for optimal quality.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I cook with expensive Champagne?</h3>
<p>Use mid-range Champagne for cooking rather than premium bottles. Cooking eliminates the subtle differences that justify high prices, making bottles in the $50-80 range ideal for reductions and sauces. Reserve expensive Champagnes for drinking, where you can appreciate their complexity.</p>
</div>
